{
  "doc_id": "16817",
  "text": "It is widely acknowledged that the hypothalamus, which in humans develops primarily prenatally but in rodents develops postnatally, plays an important role in the programming of body mass [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . To date, major efforts have been directed at understanding the roles of leptin and insulin in this process [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . However, studies in our laboratory using leptin-deficient ob/ob mice demonstrated that leptin-independent mechanisms are likely to also programme body mass [CITATION_7] .",
